			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: A couple ideas<a name="45565"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 11 04 3:31 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Best advice in order of importance?
<br />

<br />
LISTEN
<br />

<br />
PAY ATTENTION
<br />

<br />
STFU -- if have a question ask in group / tells  not in /rs  if it is a general question don't bug the RL.  
<br />

<br />
Never have songs up on the pull/incoming.  Make sure that the puller isn't in your group so group songs are acceptable.  If not and you have a monk pulling don't cast anything at all even selo's will pull aggro.  Also don't attack anything if you have epic (group proc).  
<br />

<br />
Don't go afk without telling your group or putting someone on auto follow.
<br />

<br />
Do whatever raid leader tells you/the raid.  If he says die when you &quot;think&quot; you could fade and be ok, die.
<br />

<br />
If you are doing AoE resists and it is a key factor do not attack.  Rampage very well could be survivable.  Rampage + a riposte or two probably isn't.  
<br />

<br />
Ask the other bards in your raid for advice, normally we are nice people and will understand what you are going through.  If there are none, post here.
<br />

<br />
Learn the encounters and when it is worth it to do resists and what is required.  MB is a good example.  For most guilds that need him for progression doing AoE resists isn't worth it.  Chorus only bumps 3 resists while MB has 5 different types of AoE's.  Also chorus doesn't boost most people's resists to the point where they can actually resist.  Puretone + a VotS with PoV = resists on 90% of his abilities (note with silence it isn't worth it to twist, just do resists). 
<br />

<br />
Most guilds have raiding guidelines.  Read them and understand them.  Most work a bit differentially.
<br />
 </span></td>
